{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12236"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12236"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.04,0.04,0.51,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88492"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4758"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72695"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1924"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29972"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88492"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department after a sudden onset of a severe headache. He is unable to provide a history, and his wife reports that the headache started about three hours earlier. Since then, he has been confused. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes, and he is not very compliant with his medications. He had an aortic valve replacement three years ago. About a week ago, he had a severe ear infection and his general practitioner put him on a course of antibiotics. However, the patient does not recall taking the full course of the antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient is protecting his airway but cannot communicate well. He knows his name but not the events nor where he is. His blood pressure is 180/110 mmHg, pulse 101/min, temperature 38.3\u00b0C, and respiration rate 21/min. His right pupil is dilated and poorly reactive to light. He has neck stiffness and photophobia. An intravenous line is inserted and blood drawn for basic laboratory investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous mannitol","MRI head","Immediate burr hole","CT head","Lumbar puncture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is evidence of increased intracranial pressure. The altered mental status alone would be enough to get a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT head\u003C/strong\u003E. With the addition of cranial nerve deficits (pupil dilated and unreactive) and uncontrolled hypertension, the risk of an intracranial or subarachnoid haemorrhage is increased. The first step of management is to rule out a bleed with non-contrast CT imaging. The non contrast scan could be followed by a contrast CT or an MRI after discussion with the radiologist to see which is the best option depending on local resources and the plain CT results. Infection is a serious consideration here either from the ear infection or SBE. A plain CT head may not show this. The reporting radiologist needs to know your clinical suspicions and the urgency to supply an appropriate report. Write these on the CT request and discuss the images in person if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI head\u003C/strong\u003E would provide detailed imaging of brain structures and parenchyma but is impractical in this emergency setting as it takes longer to perform and requires a still patient. CT is preferred as it quickly shows haemorrhage and mass effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate burr hole\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate without first confirming the diagnosis and location of any bleed through imaging. While this patient may ultimately need neurosurgical intervention, performing surgery without diagnostic imaging would be dangerous. A burr hole without imaging is only considered if there is a history of trauma, a lucid interval clear localising signs and no access to imaging and rapidly deteriorating patient. Usually in rural settings when imaging and transfer would take too long.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous mannitol\u003C/strong\u003E could help reduce intracranial pressure, but should not be given before imaging confirms the diagnosis. Mannitol can worsen cerebral oedema in hyponatraemic states, can cause rebound intracranial hypertension if given repeatedly, and may worsen outcomes in intracerebral haemorrhage by promoting haematoma expansion. It is also contraindicated in severe dehydration as it can precipitate acute kidney injury. Only considered in a rapidly deteriorating patient and there is a reason to think a surgical or medical option is in the near future.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsolutely\u003C/strong\u003E contraindicated when there are signs of increased intracranial pressure until CT rules out mass effect or midline shift. Although meningitis is possible given the fever, neck stiffness and photophobia, performing a lumbar puncture before CT could risk brain herniation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter CT confirms the diagnosis, management may include neurosurgical intervention, osmotic therapy, blood pressure control, and treatment of any underlying cause such as meningitis. The priority is rapid diagnosis through CT to guide appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT head is the most appropriate diagnostic modality in patients with a suspected intracranial bleed.","Sudden onset severe headache with neurological deficits should prompt immediate imaging to rule out haemorrhage.","Lumbar puncture is contraindicated in the presence of signs of increased intracranial pressure."],"references":["Freeman WD, Aguilar MI. Intracranial hemorrhage: diagnosis and management. Neurol Clin. 2012 Feb;30(1):211-40, ix. doi: 10.1016/j.ncl.2011.09.002. PMID: 22284061. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22284061/","Imtiaz A, Toomath R. Computed tomography head scans prior to lumbar punctures in suspected meningitis. Intern Med J. 2019 Jan;49(1):55-58. doi: 10.1111/imj.13997. PMID: 29869434. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29869434/","Pedersen SH, Andresen M, Lilja-Cyron A, Petersen LG, Juhler M. Lumbar puncture position influences intracranial pressure. Acta Neurochir (Wien). 2021 Jul;163(7):1997-2004. doi: 10.1007/s00701-021-04813-3. Epub 2021 Apr 2. PMID: 33797628. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33797628/","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12236"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"